  "prompt": "When the Night King's White Walkers take children, do they become fully grown like those at end of the Game of Thrones episode \"Oathbreaker?\"",
  "response": "In \"Game of Thrones,\" when the Night King's White Walkers take children, they do not appear to become fully grown adults like the ones seen at the end of the episode \"Oathbreaker.\" Instead, the process of converting a child into a White Walker involves the child being transformed into a new, undead being, but the specifics of their growth or appearance are not deeply explored in the series. \n\nThe children taken by the White Walkers seem to become more like the wights, which are reanimated corpses, rather than fully formed White Walkers with the same abilities. The White Walkers themselves are portrayed as tall, fully grown figures, distinct from the newly made wights, who retain more of their human form, albeit as mindless, soulless zombies. The transformation process mainly emphasizes the loss of humanity and the creation of an army under the Night King's control. Therefore, while the White Walkers can convert individuals into wights, the exact nature of child conversion into White Walkers remains ambiguous in the series.",
